Image loading/preprocessing¶

We'll load in a picture of a pizza from the Collegeville bakery and see what resnet says

In [5]:
def normalize_img(X):
    """
    Subtract the mean of each channel, and then divide
    by the standard deviation of each channel
    """
    mu = torch.mean(torch.flatten(X, 1, 2), dim=1)
    # Subtract the mean from each pixel
    X = X - mu.view(3, 1, 1)
    # Divide each pixel channel by the standard deviation
    std = torch.std(torch.flatten(X, 1, 2), dim=1)
    X = X/std.view(3, 1, 1)
    return X

input_image = Image.open("collegeville_bakery.jpg")
preprocess = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize(256),
        transforms.CenterCrop(224),
        transforms.ToTensor()
    ]
)
X = preprocess(input_image)
X_Orig = X

XNorm = normalize_img(X)
XNorm = XNorm.unsqueeze(0)
print(X.shape)
probs = model(XNorm)[0, :]
probs = torch.softmax(probs, 0)
idx = torch.argmax(probs)
print(categories[idx])
plt.plot(probs.detach().numpy())

Trick Resnet¶

We'll now trick resnet into thinking this image is something else by making only very subtle changes to the image

Make the pixels of the image differentiable and tweak them just a little bit until I match a 1 hot vector with something else

During optimization, make sure the pixels stay between 0 and 1

Easiest way to do that is to actually optimize over the inverse of the logistic function on the pixels

$\sigma(u) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-u}}$¶

In [6]:
device = 'cuda'
category2idx = {x:i for i, x in enumerate(categories)}

y_target = torch.zeros(1000)
y_target[category2idx["hummingbird"]] = 1

X = torch.logit(X_Orig) # Inverse of logistic function
X = X.to(device)
X = X.requires_grad_() # Makes pixels differentiable

model = model.to(device)
y_target = y_target.to(device)

# Disable gradients on all parameters of resnet to save memory
for p in model.parameters():
    p.requires_grad_(False)

loss_fn = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam([X], lr=1e-3)
n_iters = 100
plot_idx = 0
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 10))
for i in range(n_iters):
    optimizer.zero_grad()
    XNorm = torch.sigmoid(X) # Take back to [0, 1]
    XNorm = normalize_img(XNorm)
    y_est = model(XNorm.unsqueeze(0)).flatten()
    loss = loss_fn(y_est, y_target)
    loss.backward()
    optimizer.step()

    plt.clf()
    plt.subplot(231)
    plt.imshow(np.moveaxis(X_Orig.numpy(), 0, 2))
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title("Original")
    plt.subplot(232)
    XDisp = torch.sigmoid(X).detach().cpu()
    plt.imshow(np.moveaxis(XDisp.numpy(), 0, 2))
    plt.title("Perturbed")
    plt.axis("off")
    plot_idx += 1
    plt.subplot(233)
    plt.plot(torch.softmax(y_est, 0).detach().cpu())

    top5_prob, top5_id = torch.topk(torch.softmax(y_est, 0), 5)
    s = ["{}({:.3f})".format(categories[i], p) for i, p in zip(top5_id, top5_prob)]
    s = "\n".join(s)
    plt.title(s)

    colors = ["Reds", "Greens", "Blues"]
    for k in range(3):
        plt.subplot(2, 3, 4+k)
        diff = X_Orig[k, :, :] - XDisp[k, :, :]
        plt.imshow(diff, cmap=colors[k])
        plt.axis("off")
        plt.colorbar()
    plt.savefig("Iter{}.png".format(plot_idx))

A Mathematical Note on Stability¶

The upshot is that deep neural networks lack Lipschitz continuity / stability

Def. A function $f$ is k-Lipschitz continuous if

For all $x_1$, $x_2$

$|f(x_1) - f(x_2)| \leq k|x_1 - x_2|$¶

Even though deep (convolutional) neural networks lack stability in general, there is a construction called the Scattering Transform that fixes the weights as "Morlet wavelets" and fixes the activations as "complex modulus" which turns out to be stable. Click here to see some code that implements the scattering transform in torch
